                        <additions>
                            <p>
                                <locus from="LCI" to="LCI" scheme="other"/>
                                <note>Top left corner, in pencil by a modern hand: the current signum, <quote>A 142</quote>.</note>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <locus from="SL1" to="SL1" scheme="folios"/>
                                <note>Middle of page, in black ink in the hand of former librarian <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/102622">Hyltén-Cavallius</persName>: <quote>Psalterium Davidis (Defectum)</quote>; below, in pencil by a modern hand: <quote>191 blad</quote>. Lower left, in <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/102622">Hyltén-Cavallius</persName>'s hand: <quote>Mscr. de Sec: XI:o l. XII:o.</quote> Below, in the hand of former librarian <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/102623"> Oscar Wieselgren </persName>: a note on the discovery of the fragment in the Royal Danish Library, <quote>De bägge i fotografi vidlagda bladen äro tagna efter orig. i fragmentsaml. i Khvn, Kongel. Bibl, där de af undertecknad påträffades sommaren 1919. Ang. det i Khvn befintliga bladets proveniens har upplysning ej kunnat vinnas. OWn.</quote>
                                </note>
                            </p>
                        </additions>
                        <bindingDesc>
                            <binding contemporary="false">
                                <p>Early modern binding. Tan leather over cardboard. 4 raised bands and endbands. <locus from="Spine" to="Spine" scheme="other"/>, stamped in gold: <quote>A 142</quote>; remnants of paper label.</p>
                                <p>
                                    <dimensions type="binding">
                                        <height quantity="270" unit="mm"/>
                                        <width quantity="185" unit="mm"/>
                                        <depth quantity="57" unit="mm"/>
                                    </dimensions>
                                </p>
                                <decoNote type="tooling">
                                    <p>Blind-tooled double-line borders and frames forming three rectangular panels; posterior panel blind-tooled in a lozenge pattern, centre panel undecorated, and anterior panel plain with a blind-tooled double line creating a triangle shape in each outer corner.</p>
                                </decoNote>
                                <condition>Leather slightly stained and worn. Some quires detached from modern spine, revealing binding.</condition>
                            </binding>
                        </bindingDesc>
                    </physDesc>
                    <history>
                        <origin>
                            <p> The features of the script together with the layout and the contents indicate <origPlace>
                                    <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100111">France</placeName>
                                </origPlace>, <origDate notAfter="1150" notBefore="1101">12th century, first half</origDate>. The text of the gloss appears to belong to the tradition of the <foreign xml:lang="la">Glossa ordinaria</foreign> on the Psalms, the earliest datable copy of which (Troyes, Bibliothèque municipale, 511) was donated to <orgName>Clairvaux</orgName> in <date when="1145"/> (see <bibl>
                                    <title type="short" ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/bibl/107527">Wilmart (1917)</title>
                                    <citedRange from="175" to="177" unit="page"/>
                                </bibl>). The layout of the gloss is that of the early 12th century (see <bibl>
                                    <title ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/bibl/107318">De Hamel</title>
                                    <citedRange from="14" to="15" unit="page"/>
                                </bibl>).</p>
                        </origin>
                        <provenance>
                            <p>One of the leaves which is missing from the manuscript was found in <date when="1919"/> by former librarian <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/102623">Oscar Wieselgren</persName> in the <orgName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/org/100007">Royal Danish Library</orgName> (Fragm. 3136, <locus from="Photocopy_1r" to="Photocopy_1v" scheme="folios"/> ). The fragment is catalogued there as possibly having been used as a wrapper for regional tax accounts.</p>
                        </provenance>
                        <acquisition>
                            <p>Acquisition date unknown, but the manuscript has belonged to the <orgName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/org/100004">National Library</orgName> since at least the 17th century; it is listed in Jaches's catalogue of 1695 as no. <quote>387</quote> and in his catalogue of 1698 (U 122) as no. <quote>226</quote>.</p>
                        </acquisition>
                    </history>
